<title>
Type 3 deiodinase and consumptive hypothyroidism: a common mechanism for a rare disease.
</title>

<text>

<abstract>
The major product secreted by the thyroid is thyroxine (T4), whereas most of the biologically active triiodothyronine (T3) derives from the peripheral conversion of T4 into T3. The deiodinase enzymes are involved in activation and inactivation of thyroid hormones (THs). Type 1 and type 2 deiodinase (D1 and D2) convert T4 into T3 whereas D3 degrades T4 and T3 into inactive metabolites and is thus the major physiological TH inactivator. The hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis maintains circulating TH levels constant, while the deiodinases tissue-specifically regulate intracellular thyroid status by controlling TH action in a precise spatio-temporal fashion. Here we review the data related to the recent identification of a paraneoplastic syndrome called "consumptive hypothyroidism," which exemplifies how deiodinases alter substantially the concentration of TH in blood. This syndrome results from the aberrant uncontrolled expression of D3 that can induce a severe form of hypothyroidism by inactivating T4 and T3 in defined tumor tissue. This rare TH insufficiency generally affects patients in the first years of life, and has distinct features in terms of diagnosis, treatment, and prognosis with respect to other forms of hypothyroidism.
</abstract>

<sections.0>
Introduction
hyroid hormones (s) are circulating hormones widely involved in the development and metabolic homeostasis of virtually all mammalian tissues. lterations in serum  levels in the fetus and newborns cause significant deficits in experimental animals and in humans (1). he importance of maintaining the -dependent transcriptional signature range is supported by the presence of diverse homeostasis checkpoints. n fact, beyond the hypothalamus-pituitary-thyroid axis, which responds to changes in serum levels of thyroid-stimulating hormone () (2), there are various ways to affect thyroid status in a specific tissue. irst,  exerts its genomic action only in tissues that express a thyroid hormone receptor (), and second, it is possible to locally modulate the amount of  available for cells at a pre-receptoral level.  transporters and deiodinases are important in determining the availability of  in a tissue-specific manner.
lthough s are lipophilic molecules, they require specific plasma membrane transporters to enter target cells. arious transporter families have been identified, but only monocarboxylate transporters 8 and 10 (8 and 10) and anion transporting polypeptide 11 (11) have elevated specificity for s. hese proteins are differentially expressed in several tissues: 11 is expressed in liver, kidney, and brain, 8 is highly expressed in liver and brain, and 10 is expressed in intestine, kidney, liver, and placenta.  further level of complexity results from the capacity of these transporters to determine the efflux of s from the intracellular environment to the external milieu (3). he clinical relevance of these transporters is supported by evidence that mutations in the gene encoding 8 are associated with elevated serum triiodothyronine (3) levels and severe sex-linked psychomotor retardation (llanβ€“erndonβ€“udley syndrome) (4).
nce inside the nucleus, 3 acts through the binding to ligand-dependent transcription factors namely s, which bind, mainly as heterodimers with retinoid- receptors, to  response elements in target genes (5). s are encoded by two genes,  and , which are located on chromosomes 17 and 3, respectively. ± has one 3-binding splice product, ±1, predominantly expressed in brain, heart, and skeletal muscle, and two non-3-binding splice products, ±2 and ±3, and several additional truncated forms. ² has three major 3-binding splice products: ²1 is almost ubiquitously expressed; ²2 is expressed primarily in the brain, pituitary, retina, and inner ear; and ²3 is expressed in kidney, liver, and lung (6).
elenodeiodinases catalyze the activation (1 and 2) and inactivation (3) of the s thyroxine (4) and 3,5,3β€²-triiodothyronine (3) by removing distinct iodine moieties. 1 and 2 convert thyroxine into the most active metabolic form of , 3, by outer ring deiodination; and 3 converts 4 and 3 into the inactive forms r. T3 and 3,3β€²-diiodiothyronine (T2), respectively, by inner ring deiodination. D1 is expressed mostly in the liver, kidney, thyroid, and pituitary; D2 is expressed primarily in the thyroid, central nervous system, pituitary, developing cochlea, brown adipose tissue, and skeletal muscle; D3 is prevalently expressed in many fetal tissues, through the adult it is expressed in placenta, brain, and skin, and to a lesser extent in the pregnant uterus and pancreatic B-cells. The three deiodinases exert different actions: D1 participates in T3 production within the thyroid gland and controls circulating T3 levels, whereas D2 and D3 are active in local deiodination processes. Recent evidence indicates that D1 and D2 are the major sources of circulating T3 in euthyroid humans, with D1 being the major source of circulating T3 in hyperthyroid patients (7). Conversely, D3 inactivates T3 at tissue and plasma level (8). A dramatic example of the potency of the D3 pathways in TH clearance, at both systemic and tissue level, is the newly identified consumptive hypothyroidism syndrome, which is a rare condition resulting from increased D3 production in neoplastic cells and consequent T4 and T3 catabolism.
In this review, we focus on D3 as the cause of consumptive hypothyroidism, a newly recognized clinical entity which often requires close cooperation between clinical endocrinologists, pediatricians, and oncologists.
