Can regnancy be onsidered a ild orm of β€�onsumptive ypothyroidismβ€�?
regnancy is a physiological condition characterized by changes in thyroidal economy due to a combination of pregnancy-related factors that determine the need for increased  production. uring pregnancy, thyroid function adapts to the increased concentration of 4-binding globulin, the effect of chorionic gonadotropin on maternal thyroid function, the increased requirement of iodine, and the effect of placental deiodinases on  concentration. etal thyroid physiology differs greatly from maternal thyroid physiology, but the two systems interact through the placenta and amniotic fluid. hese systems control the transfer of iodine and  from the mother to the fetus (41). t is important that an appropriate amount of  be transferred from the mother to the fetus early in gestation because high  levels are deleterious for developing fetal tissues (42). herefore, the transplacental supply of  to the fetus must be finely modulated to ensure appropriate hormone levels. he deiodinases and plasma membrane transporters, which regulate the passage of  in and out of cells, are major control mechanisms for transplacental  passage (20).
etal thyroid activity begins in mid gestation, at about 18β€“20β€‰weeks.  level peaks at 24β€“28β€‰weeks, with consequent elevated 4 levels at 35β€“40β€‰weeks (43). 3 levels remain low during gestation whereas 3 causes an increase in r. T3 levels. High D3 expression has been found in human placental syncytiotrophoblasts and cytotrophoblasts, maternal deciduas, and endothelium of fetal vessels (28). During pregnancy, estrogens are potent inducers of D3 (14). Elevation of D3 during pregnancy is necessary to β€�burn offβ€� the elevated amount of T4 in maternal circulation and acts as a barrier to maternal-fetal exchanges. The injection of 700β€‰ΞΌg of T4 into amniotic fluid of pregnant women at term caused an increase of about 13-fold in amniotic fluid T3 concentration, and of about 30-fold in rT3 concentration measured 24β€‰h later (44). Thus, syncytiotrophoblasts, which express high D3 levels, can control the amount and forms of THs taken up by human placenta.
Further evidence that D3 plays a relevant role in pregnancy is the finding that at 6β€“12β€‰weeks of gestation there is a gradient of T4 from the mother to fetus, which is in the opposite direction of the rT3 gradient. In celomic and amniotic fluid, the concentration of rT3 is 3.8 and 15 times maternal levels, thereby indicating elevated D3 activity (45). The D3 activity in the maternal-fetal unit locally converts most of the T4 derived from the mother into rT3. Low T4 and T3 levels and a high rT3 level is typical of consumptive hypothyroidism. Thus, pregnancy could be considered a physiological form of compensated β€�consumptive hypothyroidism,β€� in which the β€�physiologically increasedβ€� expression of D3 increases the inactivation rate of maternal T4 thereby enhancing the need for TH.
